
## Channel Database Terminology

### Database Profile

This is a **flat / in-context** channel database — all channels are loaded into
memory and matched by name patterns and descriptions. There is no hierarchy to
navigate; instead you search, filter, and match against channel names directly.

### Terminology Mapping

Operators use domain language. Map their terms to channel name patterns:

| Operator Language | Channel Name Patterns |
|---|---|
| "beam current" | Look for channels containing `DCCT`, `BCM`, `current` |
| "BPM positions" / "beam position" | Channels containing `BPM`, `position`, possibly with `X`/`Y` suffix |
| "corrector magnets" | `HCM` (horizontal), `VCM` (vertical), `corrector`, `steering` |
| "quadrupole" / "quad" | `QF` (focusing), `QD` (defocusing), `quad` |
| "readback" / "monitor" | Channels with `RB`, `ReadBack`, `Monitor` in name |
| "setpoint" / "control" | Channels with `SP`, `Set`, `Setpoint`, `Control` in name |
| "temperature" | `Temp`, `TC`, `temperature` patterns |
| "vacuum" / "pressure" | `VGC`, `CCG`, `pressure`, `vacuum` patterns |
| "RF" / "radio frequency" | `RF`, `LLRF`, `cavity`, `frequency` patterns |
| "power supply" | `PS`, `PSU`, `supply`, `current` (in magnet context) |

### Channel Naming Conventions

- Channel names in flat databases are often **descriptive identifiers**
  (e.g., `StorageRing_BeamCurrent_ReadBack`)
- The actual PV address may differ from the descriptive name — the one subagent
  tool (`query_channels`) resolves addresses and returns the final answer
- When descriptions are available, prefer matching on description content over name
  patterns — descriptions use more natural language
